We can see that Stargell was one of the most prolific power hitters of all-time when one takes into account the following facts: the extended pitching dominance in the 60s, the post-integration surge of players into the 1970s, and his long time home park Forbes Field was notoriously hard on left-handed batters. It is interesting to see what speculation was written about Stargell in the second to last paragraph of his SABR bio:

At the time of his retirement, Stargellâs 475 home runs tied him with Stan Musial for 15th on the all-time list. As legendary a power hitter as he was, one is still tempted to ask, âWhat if?â What if he hadnât played eight-and-a-half years in the home run graveyard of Forbes Field? What if his knees had held up? What if he had been more serious about staying in shape early in his career? Four-hundred-seventy-five home runs, of course, is an extraordinary achievement. But one could imagine how a consistently healthy, consistently fit Stargell shooting at a more inviting right field porch could have boosted that total to well over 500; maybe even, as he suggested himself, close to 600.

Our method has Stargell at 526 era-adjusted home runs when we project his career in to the context beginning in 1977, which, although 526 is still far from 600, it is easy to imagine that a healthy Stargell would be close to 600. If one were to project his stats into the launch angle and exit velolicity context of the current era (current at the time that this was written) then Stargellâs totals should be right around 600. So Willie Stargell got it right. He would hit close to 600 home runs, if he were consistently fit and moved to a more forgiving ball park. Willie Stargell is a casuality of the WAR movement and era-adjusted WAR does not revitalize his image. But we should think of Stargell as one of the most efficient and prolific home run hitters of all time. This is the mental image we should have in mind when we think of Willie Stargell.

Max Scherzer

Max Scherzer is one of this eraâs greatest pitchers. He is one of a handfull of pitchers to win 3 Cy Young awards. Other players with 3 Cy Young awards include Roger Clemens, Randy Johnson, Greg Maddux, Steve Carlton, Tom Seaver, Pedro Martinez, Clayton Kershaw, Sandy Koufax, and Jim Palmer. Scherzerâs run from 2013-2019 is especially dominant. Over that stretch he collected his Cy Young awards and never fell below fifth in the voting. That being said, his numbers over that stretch do not leap off of the page. Sure, his strikeout rates and strike outs per walk ratios are all-time elite, but ERA and most counting totals do not reflect the Cy Young voting when viewed from the lens of baseball history. Take Tom Seaver as an example. From 1969 to 1975 Terrific Tom boasted similar dominance and also collected 3 Cy Young awards. In 1971 Seaver had a 1.76 ERA over 286.1 innings. Surely his run leaps off the page.

Max Scherzerâs dominance is punished by his era, a time period with a large MLB eligible talent pool, lower innings totals, and a balance of hitting and pitching that was tilted in the favor of pitching which, in this case, led to a crowded field of low ERA totals. Our per season era-adjusted statistics paint a more favorable comparison of Scherzerâs dominant 7-year run from 2013-2019 to that of Seaverâs dominant run from 1969-1975:

The Babe Ruth anomaly

Babe Ruth revolutionized baseball by prioritizing home run hitting as the MLB livened the baseball. As stated here, the single season home run record before Babe Ruth was 27 by Ned Williamson in 1884. Babe Ruth broke this record in 1919 when he hit 29 home runs. He subsequently destroyed his own record in the following 1920 season when he hit 54 home runs. The runner up in 1920 finished the season with only 15 home runs. This level of dominance has never been seen before and has never been seen since, and it poses a problem for era-adjustment techniques.

Babe Ruthâs dominance is in part due to his talent, but is also in part to him exercising a superior batting strategy that had not existed before. Therefore, Ruthâs âvs his peersâ stats are slightly distorted, and his era-adjusted stats will also be distorted as a result. Ruthâs era-adjusted stats reflect the combination of his talent and his competitive advantage. This competitive advantage does not exist in other contexts. Our method will therefore overestimate Ruthâs era-adjusted home run hitting and his era-adjusted WAR since our method does not yet disentangle talent and competitive circumstance. The problem of the Babe Ruth anomaly confounds all era-adjustment techniques. We imagine that Ruthâs era-adjusted OBP is also overestimated by our method. The Babe Ruth anomaly challenges all other era-adjustment techniques, and is especially challenging for anyone making interpretations based solely on raw or league adjusted â+â stats.

The Tony Gwynn anomaly

Tony Gwynn has the highest era-adjusted batting average by a mile (See part I). He was a truly amazing hitter who stood very far from his peers. However, like Babe Ruth, a portion of his dominance is due to circumstance. Gywnn was one of the early pioneers of using film to study his strengths and weaknesses as well as the strengths and weaknesses of the pitchers that he faced. Nowadays film study is a basic training method available to everyone in the MLB, and it is unusual and worth mentioning when great players do not use it. Therefore, like Ruth, Gwynnâs batting average stats are slightly distorted, and his era-adjusted stats will also be distorted as a result. Like Ruth, Gwynnâs era-adjusted stats reflect the combination of his talent and his competitive advantage. Our method will therefore overestimate Gwynnâs era-adjusted batting average and his era-adjusted WAR as a result.

WAR and itâs usage in HOF discussions

One of the goals of WAR is to provide a framework for people like us to compare players across eras. The following passage is taken directly from the What is WAR? page on FanGraphs: âThe goal of WAR is to provide a holistic metric of player value that allows for comparisons across team, league, year, and era and a framework for player evaluation.â

The work in this article moves WAR closer to its goal of providing fair comparisons of players who have played in vastly different eras. This matters when we evaluate a playerâs career in historical context. The HOF players of the old past are beneficiaries of biased performance metrics. Comparisons based upon âvs your peersâ statistics are therefore slanted in favor of old time playersâspecifically those who performed in the segregated NL/AL. Joe Posnanskiâs Baseball 100

Recently Joe Posnanski produced a book of the 100 greatest players of all time. While at the Athletic, Posnanski had this to say about his philosophy on ranking lists of these sort: Some of it is science, but admittedly some of it also art. I [Joe Posnanski] will give you a handful of guiding principles:

  1. I think todayâs players tend to be underrated compared to those who came before them.
  2. I lean toward players who were great at their peak, even if that peak only lasted a short time, and lean away from those who were consistently but not toweringly good for a long time.
  3. I lean toward players who did multiple things well over specialists (no matter how great) who basically did just one thing well.
  4. I take a lot of care to make educated guesses about players whose careers were shortened by things beyond their control â World War II, for example, or baseballâs tragic and infuriating color line. I donât make the same adjustment for injuries. As Bill James has written, thereâs a big difference. The years when Joe DiMaggio or Ted Williams or Bob Feller were at war, the years when Josh Gibson and Oscar Charleston played in the Negro Leagues, they were still the best players on earth. They just couldnât play in the big leagues because of larger issues. When players get hurt â take Don Mattingly, for example, and his back problems â they stop being the best players in the world. I wish Donnie Baseball didnât get hurt, we all do, but he did, and he was never quite the same player after that. Thatâs not the same as saying that Bob Feller lost four years when he was still the best pitcher on earth.

Comparing a Player Outside His Era: Bill James and Tom Tango

Bill James published a fascinating conversation between Tom Tango and himself on the subject of cross-era comparisons. There are many nuggets from this conversation which deserve attention, but in the interest of brevity, we will only focus on a few segments.

Simplifying a little, Tom Tangoâs initial position is that we should only compare players to their contemporaries in the strictest of senses. He says:

You have about 12-15 nonpitcher in the HOF for any 10-11 year time period. If Andruw Jones [a player whose HOF candidcay that Bill and Tom are discussing] is one of the top 12 nonpitcher among his peers, great. If heâs one of the 40 nonpitchers born 1962-1992, great. (Though these numbers can be argued based on expansion.)â¦ This way, we donât have to make âtimelineâ adjustments. Thatâs me though.

Billâs response is very lengthy (although not as lengthy as what you have read here). One of his main points of response is:

Yes, of course it is difficult to make cross-generational comparisons in baseball, but you ignore the fact that we have a constant frame of reference which applies across time and which stabilizes the data across time: Wins. IF you can state a playerâs contribution to his team in terms of wins and losses, then you have a valid basis for comparing a player from 1968 to a player in 2008âleaving only the large problem of the relative quality of play over time, and the relatively small issues of the length of the schedule and what to do with post-season play.

And, in fact, we HAVE 85% solved the problem(s) of stating a playerâs contribution to his team in terms of wins and losses. Yes, we still have the WAR/Wins and Losses Issue and the many problems inherent in WAR, but what we DO know about this issue now is much larger than what we do not knowâunlike 1975, when we had not even reached the understanding that we needed to state these contributions in constant terms, and that wins was the constant unit which guides the debate.

Tom responds with:

Inherent in the wins-as-the-great-equalizer debate is that it treats winning percentage of .500 as a constant. This forces a specific mindset: (a) do you adjust this across time, so that a .500 win% in 1917 is not the same as in 2017? (b) do you accept it is the same, solely for the purposes of peer-comparisons?

If you accept (b), weâre holding the players accountable to their era only. And so any comparison of Ty Cobb to Rickey Henderson is limited to their comparisons to their direct peers, and then players of the early 1900s, as a group, are being treated as equals to the players of the 1980s and of today (.500 = .500). So, weâre actually comparing Cobb and Rickey through this âcommon baselineâ.

If you accept (a), you need to accept that players have gotten better across time, just like in every other sport, and so, the average player in Cobbâs time would likely be a bench player today, at best. I say this not only because players must have gotten physically stronger and faster, but also because 3/8ths of the best players today would have been precluded from playing during the segregation era. If we use players of the 1900s as any kind of benchmark, by this assumption, weâd be voting in ten players every year.

In my view, before we jump through the hoops that a careful timeline comparison would require, (including establishing which of the two assumptions to follow, of which no one will agree with anyway) letâs at least do the easy part and compare players to their direct peers.

We are now going to interject ourselves into this conversation. In our view, the Full House Model IS the careful timeline comparison sought by Tom Tango, and it renders his mindset distinctions between (a) and (b) moot. The Full House Model takes statistics like WAR and corrects for its existing era-biases through a balancing of how one performs âvs their peersâ and how many people are eligible to play in the MLB.

Tom is right when he suggests that we would be voting in more players every year if we actually approach HOF candidates by their era-adjusted talent. It seems that he is stating this as a drawback which, if true, would be very disappointing considering that older playersâ statistics are inflated as a result of racial segregation.

Now there are cold emotionless era-adjusted statistics which back up Christina Kahrl. We can all now spend much less frustration mentally trying to unwind a previously intractable problem. Our method may not be perfect, but the big step of correcting for the talent imbalances which plague commonly used statistics in a sensible way has now been undertaken.

ZiPS Projections

Dan Szymborski closes his 2021 recap article with a discussion on outlandish Juan Soto projections to which he says:

Iâll admit it: I just wanted to see Soto break ZiPS. And I think he might have. Last spring, I spent some time talking with Jayson Stark about whether Soto was the next Ted Williams. The amazing thing is that neither of us thought the idea was absurd. MLB should simply redefine the strike zone as âwhatever Juan Soto wonât swing at.â He might not always be the best overall player, but heâs the most gifted offensive player of this generation.

Here are the outlandish percentile Soto projections that Szymborski references:

Szymborski refers to Soto as breaking ZiPS. In other words, the projection system is unreliable for Soto. We do not think that players break projection systems. Rather, projection systems are themselves broken if they produce nonsensical forecasts for players. We do not know the inner mechanics of the ZiPS Projection System. If it borrows information from great players of the past to inform predictions about great players of the present, then its outputs may reflect era biases which have been discussed throughout this work. In a very unpopular public comment that was inspired by Harry Craneâs 2018 article on election forecasting, Eck was willing to bet the under of the ZiPS 90th percentile of the Soto projections under the premise that it may have embedded era biases. Eck received a lot of public flack but ultimately got zero takers. We appreciate Dan Szymborski for even taking the time to acknowledge the circus that surrounded our point. We also enjoyed Danâs amusing reveal that an unadulterated Ted Williams is indeed Juan Sotoâs closest comp.

We now take a closer look at the wider field of Williamsâs competition. Below we display the distributions of ebWAR values of all pitchers who pitched at least 150 innings for each of the above AL eras with a focus on comparing Williamsâs AL to the other eras. We find that the field of pitchers that Williams faced is slightly better than the era that came before it (which makes sense) and slightly worse than the contemporaneous NL. But his competition was far worse than the more modern eras.

What this shows is that Ted Williams faced some of the weakest competition that one could have faced over a lengthy career. Or, in other words, if you could choose a contextual environment with the goal of maximizing your potential for achieving mythical stats, then the 1939-1960 AL with Lefty Grove on your team would have to be near the top of the list. Moreover, Ted Williams was a left-handed hitter and Lefty Grove was a left-handed pitcher (his real name is not Lefty). This is important because Ted Williams was relatively weak against left-handed pitching. So Ted had it comparatively easier than others.

In addition, Ted Williams faced fewer left handed-hitters than great hitters from more modern eras. Kenneth Matinale has some analyses on this topic, you can view one here. Below are Ted Williams splits from baseball reference (the information is not based on complete play-by-play data). We can see that Williams was far worse against left-handed pitchers, and that he faced lefties only 21.8% of the time. On the other hand, Tony Gywnn and George Brett faced lefties, respectively, 34.4% and 33.2% of the time.

We use a wOBA based approach to estimate Williamsâs era-adjusted WAR had 33% of his plate appearances came against lefties using the run values computed here. This reference gives run values for outs (-0.26), walks (0.29), HBP (0.31), singles (0.44), doubles (0.74), triples (1.01), and home runs (1.39). We will suppose that one run is 0.10 WAR (using a 10 runs-to-wins conversion). Note that Williams loses more home runs than hits. We assign a run value of 0.59 for this difference so that theses added hits are halfway between a single and a double. The analysis here shows that Ted Williamsâs era-adjusted stats would take a substantial hit if they were additionally adjusted for a more modern pitching deployment strategy, one that was embraced during the time frame that we are using to evaluate careers.

Where does this go from here? Ted Williams needs only roughly 21 efWAR to eclipse Greg Maddux for the 4th spot in efWAR or roughly 25 efWAR to take the 3rd spot from Babe Ruth (who faced Walter Johnson and performed almost as well against Lefty Grove as Williams did against the anonymous lefties of his day). Barry Bonds who put up 8.36 efWAR in 1998 is ahead of Ted Williams so he needs fewer efWAR to achieve the same heights. Mike Trout is on the outside looking in, but he is the most productive player all-time on a rate-basis, and he dwarfs Williams in this regard. A close look at Williamsâs stats reveal that he got off to a hot start in 1953 (which is possibly overvalued by our smoothing method) and his 1941 and 1946 seasons were exceptional so he could pull this off. But none of this accounts for the relatively poor pitching competition that Ted Williams faced in his time period. How much should that factor in? A 5% reduction? A 10% reduction? More? Less? And how do these types of projections account for injury risk?

It seems like a tall order for Ted Williams to crack the Mount Rushmore career ranking of all players from the analysis, even when viewing his career and his projections favorably. The same exercise viewed through ebWAR wouldnât give him much hope of cracking the Mount Rushmore. Ted Williams remains one of the greatest players all-time. But the mythical lore that surrounds him reflects failed attempts to properly evaluate the historical achievements of players. Ted Williams is Joey Votto (through 2021) with more power and more longevity, and a slightly lower OBP. Oh the blasphemy

In all, we do not see Ted Williams in the Mt Rushmore of the gameâs all-time greatest players. Anyone placing him that high is likely blinded by his transcendent stats which were accumulated in an extremely beneficial context, and is giving him a charitable projection for the seasons he missed while harshly punishing others. We hope that our analysis will shed light on Ted Williams accomplishments, and we hope that the reader will see that the real Ted Williams remains a truly great player. Being Joey Votto with more power and more longevity is truly great.
